          "title": "The perfection of the Rock (32:1-4) — the standard that makes rebellion inexcusable",
          "body": "Before Moses indicts Israel, he establishes the character of the God against whom they have sinned. Four attributes stack in verse 4: perfect work (*tamim*), just ways (*mishpat*), faithfulness (*emunah*), and no injustice (*evel*). The fourfold description is not rhetorical inflation — it is the legal standard against which every subsequent charge will be measured. Israel cannot claim their covenant partner was arbitrary, capricious, or unjust. The Rock's perfection is the very thing that makes Israel's rebellion culpable rather than excusable. Verse 4 is the constitutional premise of the entire lawsuit: the judge is perfect, and the covenant He made was perfect, and the provision He gave was perfect. Every 'but' and 'yet' in the poem's indictment section derives its moral force from this foundation. John Calvin, commenting on the Psalms' Rock imagery, notes that the metaphor unites stability of being with stability of promise — the God who IS the Rock cannot be moved from His commitments, for good or ill."
